ANTH G6186.  PERFORMING SUBJECTIVITY IN AN AGE OF REVOLUTION: OPERA AND=20
STORYTELLING.  308 Lewisohn, Thurs: 4:10-6 pm.  Prof. Combs-Schilling.=20
Office hours for this class are immediately after class in Lewisohn or=20
in 956 Schermerhorn by appointment. mec3@columbia.edu

The course examines opera performances as a site for negotiating=20
changes in images of persons, gender, political authority and community=20
as eighteenth century Europe headed towards revolution.  By focusing=20
broader analytical frameworks (e.g., those of Butler, Eco, Feldman,=20
Geertz, Hull and Tambiah) on five eighteenth century operas, expansive=20
light can be shed on the potential potency of lyric storytelling to be=20
a generative site of culture.  We will explore ways in which particular=20
operas expanded the range of alternatives available to individuals and=20
communities as well as ways in which prominent political cultural=20
filters reduced ways in which particular operas could be understood.  =20
Included in our exploration will be the issue of how these operas=20
resonate now and whether any of them still challenge images of gender,=20
persons and community.

This is an interdisciplinary course designed for those who are=20
interested in the role collective performances can play in producing=20
cultural imaginations-narrative and lyric.  It is intended to appeal to=20
graduate students from a wide range of disciplines, including:=20
anthropology, drama, English, gender studies, German, history, Italian,=20
literary studies and music as well as those who specialize in=20
eighteenth century studies.  Cultural rather than musicological=20
approaches are emphasized.  While musical expertise is not demanded, it=20
is a most welcome addition.  Specific student projects will be designed=20
according to the individual student's own interests and expertise.

The five operas to be explored are Thomas Arne and Metastasio's=20
Artaxerses (1762 London), Paisiello and Petrosellini's Barber of=20
Seville (1783 Vienna), Paisiello and Casti's King Theodore (1784=20
Vienna) as well as Mozart and Da Ponte's Marriage of Figaro (1786=20
Vienna) and Cosi fan Tutte (Women are Like That) (1789 Vienna).   We=20
will see Marriage and Cosi at the Metropolitan Opera House as well as=20
one other opera of the student's choice.
=09
Course limited to 15 students.   Those interested should e-mail Prof.=20
Combs-Schilling at mec3@columbia.edu with a few sentences expressing=20
their interest in the course and their areas of expertise.  All=20
interested students must attend the first class.


